  "prompt": "Why do jain sadhus do not wear clothes?",
  "response": "Jain sadhus, or ascetics, often choose to go without clothes as a part of their spiritual practice, which emphasizes non-attachment, renunciation, and the pursuit of liberation (moksha). This practice is rooted in several key principles of Jainism:\n\n1. **Non-attachment**: Jainism teaches that attachment to material possessions, including clothing, can lead to bondage in the cycle of birth and rebirth (samsara). By renouncing clothes, sadhus demonstrate their commitment to overcoming worldly attachments.\n\n2. **Aparigraha (non-possessiveness)**: This principle encourages individuals to minimize their possessions and desires. By forgoing clothing, sadhus embody this ideal by not claiming ownership of anything, even garments.\n\n3. **Simplicity and humility**: Going unclothed symbolizes a life of simplicity and humility, reinforcing their commitment to spiritual goals over material concerns.\n\n4. **Living in accordance with their vows**: Jain ascetics take strict vows, including those of non-violence (ahimsa) and truthfulness. Their lifestyle choices, including the decision to remain unclothed, are expressions of these vows.\n\n5. **Detachment from the physical body**: By not wearing clothes, sadhus also aim to transcend the physical identity and focus more on the spiritual aspect of existence.\n\nIt is important to note that not all Jains practice nudity; this practice is more common among certain sects, such as the Digambara sect. Other Jains may wear simple, minimal clothing while still adhering to the core principles of their faith.",
